    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper asks whether ignoring a specific orbital phenomenon \u2014 transient resonances, which occur when an inspiralling object's orbital frequencies reach a simple ratio \u2014 would cause scientists to misread the properties of gravitational-wave sources in future space-based detectors like LISA. The review board finds the qualitative warning credible: the paper presents consistent evidence that these resonances leave a detectable imprint, and that modeling their sign and amplitude correctly is important. However, two structural limitations of the analysis mean the specific numerical bias estimates should not be taken at face value, and the results should be read as a well-motivated case study rather than a definitive quantitative forecast.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper applies a Fisher-matrix analysis \u2014 using numerical kludge (NK) waveforms augmented by a phenomenological effective resonance model (ERM) with orbit-dependent Teukolsky-based coefficients \u2014 to estimate systematic parameter bias when resonance crossings are omitted from template waveforms. Two objections survived all review cycles: (1) the Cutler-Vallisneri first-order bias formula is applied in large-mismatch regimes (mismatches up to 1.030) where the authors themselves acknowledge it is invalid, so tabulated bias ratios in those cases are qualitative indicators only; and (2) the Fisher parameter space excludes extrinsic parameters under an unvalidated degeneracy assumption, which likely deflates statistical error bounds and inflates the bias-to-uncertainty ratios. The strongest internally-consistent finding is that sign and amplitude of resonance-induced modifications to the constants of motion are decisive, with sign changes moving weaker-resonance biases across the significance threshold \u2014 a result that does not depend on the large-mismatch regime."
    }
